<li id="mwBl4"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Silke_Leopold" title="Silke Leopold" about="#mwt320" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"ill","href":"./Template:Ill"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Silke Leopold"},"2":{"wt":"de"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBl8" class="new">Silke Leopold</a><span class="noprint" style="font-size:85%; font-style: normal; " about="#mwt320" id="mwBmA"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity">[</span><a rel="mw:WikiLink/Interwiki" href="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silke%20Leopold" title="de:Silke Leopold">de</a><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Interlanguage_link_template_link_number#A"/><span typeof="mw:Entity">]</span></span>, "The Idea of National Opera, c. 1800", <i id="mwBmE">United and Diversity in European Culture c. 1800</i>, ed. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./T._C._W._Blanning" title="T. C. W. Blanning" id="mwBmI">Tim Blanning</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hagen_Schulze" title="Hagen Schulze" id="mwBmM">Hagen Schulze</a> (New York: Oxford University Press, 2006), 19–34.</li>
